<solution><div><p/><h3>Worked solution</h3>
<p>A conic in the two-dimensional plane is the solution set of an equation of the form</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle ax^{2}+bxy+cy^{2}+dx+ey+f=0</m></p>
<p>for real parameters <m>\displaystyle a,b,c,d,e</m> and <m>f,</m> where at least one of the <m>a,b</m> and <m>c</m> is not zero.</p>
<p>If <m>\displaystyle b^{2}-4ac &gt;0</m> then the graph is a hyperbola (or two intersecting lines).</p>
<p> Consider the following equation: <m>\displaystyle x^{2}+Bxy=F</m>.</p>

<p><m>\displaystyle a={1},b={B},c=0,f={-F}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle b^{2}−4ac=B^{2}−4(1)(0)={B^2} &gt;0,B \neq 0</m>.</p>
<p>Therefore, the graph of <m>\displaystyle x^{2}+Bxy=F,</m> is a hyperbola or two intersecting lines, if <m>B \neq 0</m>. </p>
<p> Case 1: If <m>\displaystyle F \neq 0,</m>  we have;</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle y={\frac{F}{B x}-\frac{x}{B}}</m>, thus the graph is a hyperbola.</p>
<p> Case 2: If <m>\displaystyle F = 0, x^{2}+Bxy=0,</m>  we have; </p>
<p><m>\displaystyle x={0}</m> and <m>y={-\frac{x}{B}}</m>, thus the graph represents two intersecting lines.</p>
<p>As a result, the graph is a hyperbola when <m>F\neq 0</m> and intersecting lines when <m>F=0</m>.</p></div></solution>
